<HEADLINE>
<P>
IT'S COW-COW BOOGIE ON DELHI ROADS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Lay off the horn, slow down, and above all, don't wear red. 
</P>
<P>
 The cows are back on New Delhi's streets, and not by popular demand. But did 
that ever stop them? 
</P>
<P>
 Not last year, not this year. Thousands of cows have invaded the city, 
snarling traffic and making children pass within inches of cows and bulls as 
they walk to school. 
</P>
<P>
 Crashing into a cow, or even nudging one aside with a bumper, is sinful for 
most Hindus, who worship the beasts as "go-matas," or mother cows. 
</P>
<P>
 They wander down New Delhi's streets all year, but during good monsoons -- 
like the current one -- they take to the warmth of the roads in great numbers 
to avoid their rain-soaked sheds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA082194-0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 071745 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
August 21, 1994, Sunday, Bulldog Edition 
</P>
