<HEADLINE>
<P>
RUSSIAN INVOLVEMENT SEEN IN NUCLEAR SMUGGLING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 German police fear some Russian officials are involved in the smuggling of 
nuclear material, a senior aide to Chancellor Helmut Kohl said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Bernd Schmidbauer, Kohl's intelligence coordinator, made the comment in 
discussing why police did not notify their Russian counterparts of a sting 
designed to collar a suspected nuclear smuggler. 
</P>
<P>
 "This isn't an accusation, but rather the point that must be discussed in 
Moscow -- working together," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Schmidbauer was to fly to Moscow on Saturday with Germany's top intelligence 
chiefs and nuclear scientists in an effort to coordinate actions against 
nuclear smuggling. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials in Moscow have denied that weapons-grade nuclear materials have been 
spirited out of Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
