<HEADLINE>
<P>
BONDS PLEADS HARDSHIP, WINS CASE AS JUDGE PROVES TO BE FAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Barry Bonds, who would have made $4.75 million this season if there had been 
no baseball strike, asked a judge to cut his $15,000-per-month child and 
spousal support payments in half. Bonds pleaded financial hardship because of 
the strike. 
</P>
<P>
 George Taylor, a domestic relations commissioner, granted the request -- and 
then asked for Bonds' autograph. 
</P>
<P>
 Bonds' agent, Dennis Gilbert, said in a court declaration that because of the 
strike, Bonds can't afford the $15,000 monthly payment. He said Bonds will get 
only $24,000 to $30,000 in licensing money that has been withheld by the Major 
League Baseball Players Assn. 
</P>
<P>
 Bonds' estranged wife, Sun, initially sought $262,000 per month for spousal 
and child support. She has since dropped her request to about $130,000 per 
month, according to records. 
</P>
<P>
 Lawrence Stotter, lawyer for Sun Bonds, said Taylor's autograph request 
"really wiped out my client." 
</P>
<P>
 "To have the courts look upon (Bonds) as a superhero made her feel like she 
was not playing on a level playing field." 
</P>
<P>
 Taylor was unavailable for comment Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
