<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: VENTURA; RIP CURRENTS POSE RISK TO BEACH-GOERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT HADLY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Rip currents in Ventura waters have resulted in 10 near drownings in the last 
six days, a head lifeguard at the San Buenaventura State Beach said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
 Eight people in two separate incidents Saturday afternoon were swept into the 
ocean by rip currents along the unguarded beach south of the Ventura Harbor 
near Surfers Knoll, said Kirk Sturm a lifeguard supervisor with the State 
Beach. 
</P>
<P>
 "That beach is known to have rip currents all the time," he said. "People have 
to realize that on these beaches with no lifeguards they shouldn't enter the 
water. It can be dangerous any time." 
</P>
<P>
 Seven people were swept into the ocean about 3 p.m. Saturday, Sturm said. Five 
lifeguards, one park ranger and one member of the Ventura Harbor Patrol had to 
swim out to pull the beach-goers from the water, he said. No one was seriously 
hurt in the incident, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Sturm said lifeguards Keith Mullaney, 24, and Rachel Thompson, 21, sprinted 
half a mile from Marina Cove Beach and were the first rescuers in the water. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think they deserve some kind of medal," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 More than 5,000 people crowded area beaches Saturday, with close to half of 
those on the unguarded beaches north of the Ventura Pier and south of the 
Ventura Harbor, Sturm said. More are expected today. SCOTT HADLY 
</P>
</TEXT>
